The Federal Capital Territory Administration (FCTA) said that it has commenced the payment of the N30, 000 new minimum wage to civil servants working in the administration. The administration also disclosed that it has cleared over N4 billion salary arrears to workers, from April last year till date. Director, FCT treasury department, Ismail Ishiaku, who disclosed this to journalists in Abuja yesterday, said that the move followed the agreement reached between organised labour and government. Ishiaku revealed that the January salaries will hit the accounts of workers this week, noting that the move by the FCT administration to pay minimum wage arrears at once, was to enable workers start the year on a financially stable note. While calling on workers to re-double their efforts in the discharge of their duties, the director assured civil servants of the ministers’ commitment on timely payment of salaries and other welfare packages due to them. According to him, “The minimum wage was to start, effective from April 2019 but its implementation began in December 2019 and because the directive from the federal government came after the FCT had already paid the December salary, we calculated the arrears in the second week of January”. “We calculated the arrears from April to December, 2019. In other words, we have paid for December. So, we have paid the minimum wage from April to December last year as the effective date for the new minimum wage based on the agreement with labour was April 2019.”